Alibaba Group (BABA US & 9988 HK), China (Alex Yao)
Building for Tomorrow: Clear Roadmap to Efficiency, Synergies, and Long- Term Value

Alibaba's JuneQ25 results strengthen our confidence in its mid- to long- term earnings outlook. We expect streamlined operations, strong financial resources, and clear strategies in quick commerce and cloud to drive sustainable double- digit earnings growth. While near- term profits face pressure from quick commerce investment, we believe efficiency gains and ecosystem synergies should support a stronger long- term trajectory. We cut our FY26 adj EPS by \(13\%\) and raise our FY27 adj EPS by \(6\%\) . Maintain OW with Jun- 26 PT of US\$170/HK\$165 on 12x CY2027E P/E.
Trip.com (TCOM US and 9961 HK), China (Alex Yao)
Well- positioned across time horizons: Cyclical momentum + structural growth

TCOM has underperformed the sector average, as measured by KWEB, by 10ppts in the past three months, due to investor concerns about JD's potential entrance into the China domestic OTA market and a negative impact from a lackluster travel market during summer. We believe TCOM's solid 2Q25 result and healthy financial outlook for 3Q25 should dismiss investor concerns and drive share price upside. As a market leader in OTA with a strong foot print in mid to high- end consumers, TCOM looks well positioned to capture the following near- term and long- term trends: spillover effect from an A- share rally, outbound travel, international OTA expansion and inbound travel. Maintain OW with a new PT of US\$90/HK\$700 as we rollover our valuation base to 2026 with the same 20x target multiple.
Longfor Group (0960) (0960. HK, OW - HK\$10.58), China (Karl Chan)

For investors who want to play a medium- term turnaround story among non- SOE Chinese developers, we believe Longfor remains the best candidate with favourable risk- reward, because: 1) default risk is low with a comfortable balance sheet; 2) recurring net income of Rmb8- 9bn provides a solid buffer; 3) management remains one of the more capital- market- friendly ones (peers such as Vanke & Seazen no longer host result briefings, while Longfor not only hosts a results call, but also remains active in roadshows & conferences). Tactically, if there is significant policy easing in the housing market, we believe Longfor may offer \(>70\%\) upside if we simply benchmark to the peak in October 2024. However, even if we assume 'no big policy', we believe Longfor may still retare gradually to \(\sim \mathsf{HK}\$ 14\) (33% potential upside) in the medium term, if we apply a 10x P/E to recurring (non- DP) net income (assuming zero value from DP). From a trading perspective, we
also observe Longfor seems to have found a solid support level at \(>HK\$ 9\) .

BYD's 2Q25 earnings came in \(30\%\) shy of expectations as a result of fierce price competition during the quarter that weighed on the GPM. A record- level price discount seen in the entire industry in June has started to narrow after the government's "anti- involution" efforts. Management believes profitability should start to rebound in 3Q25. Longer term, our view on BYD remains unchanged, especially regarding its overseas expansion where capacity- build (i.e. Indonesia, Brazil, and Hungary) is one to two quarters ahead of plan. We thus forecast the overseas business to contribute to around half of BYD's total profit, up from \(\sim 40\%\) this year. We cut our 2025/26 estimates by \(21\% /7\%\) to reflect the results and thus reduce our Jun- 26 share price targets to HK\$150/Rmb140.
Techtronic Industries (0669) (0669. HK, OW - HK\$100.40), China (Karen Li, CFA)

We are taking TTI off the Catalyst Watch as the stock has played out (+15% vs. HSI index \(+4\%\) since mid- July), in light of positive read- throughs from sales channels, US interest rate cut expectations, etc. Despite this, we stay bullish given the company's enhanced growth outlook. TTI's acquisition of a \(5.03\%\) stake in Japan's Ryobi (5851 JP; source: Bloomberg) reinforces its global brand ecosystems and aids the expansion into the Japanese market challenging the incumbent Makita. Additionally, positive read- throughs from Home Depot and Lowe's recently announced 2Q25 results, along with optimism for US interest rate cuts, tax reform and accelerating industrialization, bolster TTI's growth prospects amid the expanding global power tool TAM. With these developments, we are raising our PT to HK\$135, reflecting our confidence in TTI's ability to achieve robust earnings growth in the forecast period. Maintain OW.

SOE banks 2Q25 print - a beat. Profits growth turned positive at \(+2.3\%\) y/y (vs 1Q25 - \(1.6\%\) y/y). While profits growth was largely in line with expectations, revenue and PPoP growth beat expectations, with \(5\% /8\%\) growth y/y in 2Q25 beating JPM by 5ppt/6ppt, respectively. The beat was led mainly by strong non- NII growth (+29% y/y), for both fee (+14% y/y) and other income (+57% y/y). We believe CCB reported the best quality 2Q print with strong revenue growth (+11% y/y), followed by ICBC with NII growth turning positive y/y. PSBC delivered the highest PPOP and profits growth, but asset quality concern and declining coverage ratio remain an overhang. ABC profits growth (+3% y/y) is 2nd highest among SOE banks, but this is largely within expectations. We expect SOE banks to see positive share price reactions - our pecking order on the 2Qprint would be CCB>ICBC>PSBC>BOC>BoCom>ABC.
Beijing Capital International Airport (0694. HK, OW - HK\$2.95), China (Jenny Qiu, CFA)

Key beneficiary of China's influx of inbound tourists; 1H25 results review and briefing takeaways In this note, we highlight Beijing Capital International Airport (BCIA)'s strong recovery of inbound tourists in Beijing City, which benefits BCIA, along with its 1H25 results and briefing takeaways. 1) Inbound tourism: unlike the well- discussed outbound segment, inbound tourists in Beijing City have already reached 130% of 2019's levels, providing a notable benefit to BCIA; 2) The 1H25 result was a non- event, with a net loss of Rmb164MM, aligning with pre- announced range. Mgmt expressed commitment to shareholder returns and efforts to further cut costs and capex. We remain OW BCIA, given muted expectations despite improving underlying trends and attractive valuation at 0.9x FY26E P/B (below its long- term mean of 1.2x) and 9.0x FY26 EV/EBITDA (below the Asia Airports average of 11.0x).
Bank of China (BOCHK) (2388) (2388HK, N - HK\\$35.22), Hong Kong (Jemmy S Huang)

BOCHK 1H25 results came in ahead of our expectation but largely in line with consensus, supported by PPOP growth remaining decent. We revise up our earnings forecasts by 26%/21% to reflect more resilient margins and trading gains and retain our Neutral rating with a new PT of HK\\$38.4.
